1 AN ACT relating to the Kentucky Kindergarten Readiness Performance-Based
2 Child Care Incentive Pilot Program.
3 WHEREAS, providing performance-based incentives to diverse types of early
4 childhood education and child-care providers leads to the expansion of services across the
5 Commonwealth; and
6 WHEREAS, providing performance-based incentives to low-income parents of
7 children not receiving services from early childhood education and child-care providers,
8 Head Start, or public Pre-K is a way to encourage parents to prepare their children for
9 kindergarten; and
10 WHEREAS, providing performance-based incentives increases the number of
11 children entering school kindergarten ready, which positively impacts future educational
12 attainment; and
13 WHEREAS, providing performance-based incentives encourages early childhood
14 education and child-care providers to provide services for children with special needs;
15 NOW, THEREFORE,
16 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
17 SECTION 1. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 199 IS CREATED TO
18 READ AS FOLLOWS:
19 (1) As used in this section:
20 (a) "Cabinet" means the Cabinet for Health and Family Services;
21 (b) "Type I child-care center" means a child-care center licensed by the cabinet
22 to regularly provide child care services for:
23 1. Four (4) or more children in a nonresidential setting; or
24 2. Thirteen (13) or more children in a designated space separate from the
25 primary residence of a licensee;
26 (c) "Type II child-care center" means a child-care center that is the primary
27 residence of the licensee in which child care is regularly provided for seven
Page 1 of 5
XXXX 2/11/2026 5:48 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1724
1 (7), but not more than twelve (12), children including children related to the
2 licensee; and
3 (d) "University" means the University of Kentucky.
4 (2) By August 1, 2026, the university shall establish and operate the Kentucky
5 Kindergarten Readiness Performance-Based Child Care Incentive Pilot Program,
6 which shall operate from January 1, 2027, until July 31, 2029.
7 (3) The pilot program shall:
8 (a) Determine how to provide performance-based incentives to diverse types of
9 early childhood education providers, child-care providers, and low-income
10 parents in order to increase the number of children in the Commonwealth
11 who are assessed as kindergarten ready;
12 (b) Determine how to best assess applicants and distribute moneys;
13 (c) Develop a written plan and implement assessment processes to determine
14 kindergarten readiness for children in the Commonwealth. The university
15 shall convene a working group to assist in the development of the written
16 plan and assessment processes;
17 (d) Ensure that participants in the pilot program represent geographically
18 diverse areas of the Commonwealth;
19 (e) Evaluate the impact of performance-based incentives implemented through
20 the pilot program using a rigorous design framework that supports causal
21 inferences;
22 (f) Design, identify, and make available resources for parents to assist them in
23 preparing children for kindergarten readiness;
24 (g) Determine how to award funds to licensed Type I and Type II child-care
25 centers; cabinet-regulated early childhood education providers, certified
26 child-care homes, and registered providers; and single or married parents
27 who qualify for the child-care subsidy administered by the cabinet pursuant
Page 2 of 5
